# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 21:11:11
overview:<p>The Mandrill holds the distinction of being the first totem BattleMech ever produced, introduced in 2829 as a light fire support design for Clan Fire Mandrill. Created by Kindraa Payne during the last period of unity within the Clan, the thirty-ton 'Mech was designed to embody the fierce spirit of the Fire Mandrill's namesake animal, featuring a distinctly simian appearance with bulky shoulders, elongated arms, and a cockpit resembling a mandrill's face. The design's unique chassis even permits it to shift between bipedal and quadrupedal gaits, using its exaggerated arms to move along the ground in a manner similar to a quad 'Mech.</p><p>Though production ceased for over a century as resources were redirected to OmniMech development, the Mandrill remained in active service across all Fire Mandrill Kindraa as a valued second-line combatant and enduring symbol of Clan identity.</p>

capabilities:<p>Despite its light tonnage, the Mandrill delivers firepower more commonly associated with medium and heavy designs. Twin Type 20 "Great Bow" LRM-20 launchers dominate the 'Mech, consuming over a third of its total mass and enabling devastating missile saturation attacks that can overwhelm opponents in the one-on-one duels favored by the Clans. A head-mounted Series 1 extended-range small laser provides a last-resort weapon when ammunition is expended, a capability that proved its worth during engagements against Clan Smoke Jaguar forces on the Clan world of Atreus.</p><p>The Mandrill's Firebox 120 XL engine limits top speed to sixty-five kilometers per hour, making it one of the slower designs in its weight class. Type C Medium Lifter jump jets partially compensate for this deficiency, providing the ability to reposition across broken terrain. Five tons of Compound FM3 ferro-fibrous armor offers adequate protection for Clan dueling conditions, though the design remains vulnerable to sustained engagements or concentrated fire. Ten double heat sinks ensure the Mandrill rarely suffers from overheating even during prolonged missile barrages.</p>

deployment:<p>The standard Mandrill carries its full complement of twin LRM-20 launchers with four tons of ammunition, supported by a single head-mounted extended-range small laser. Every Kindraa within Clan Fire Mandrill maintained at least a Star of these totem 'Mechs in their second-line forces, where the design served as both a capable fire support platform and a powerful symbol of Clan unity. Repairing and maintaining the Mandrill was considered among the most important duties assigned to the technician caste. No factory variants of the Mandrill are known to exist.</p>

history:<p>The Mandrill was born during the Golden Century, introduced in 2829 as the creation of Kindraa Payne. It represented the last truly unified effort of Clan Fire Mandrill before the Clan fractured into the competing Kindraa that would define its character for centuries. The design's simian appearance and unique movement capabilities made it an instantly recognizable symbol of the Fire Mandrills, and every Kindraa maintained these totem 'Mechs as a matter of pride and identity.</p><p>As the Clans transitioned to OmniMech technology during the late twenty-ninth century, the components that made the Mandrill successful (its XL engine, endo steel frame, and ferro-fibrous armor) were redirected to OmniMech production lines. The Mandrill itself fell out of production, though existing examples continued to serve in second-line units across all Kindraa for over a century. The design's influence extended beyond the Fire Mandrills themselves; the Jade Falcons, impressed by the concept of a light mobile missile platform, borrowed the Mandrill's design philosophy and scaled it down to create the Howler, known in the Inner Sphere by its reporting name of Baboon.</p><p>After more than a century without new production, the Mandrill received an unexpected reprieve in 3058 when Khan Amanda Carrol formally requested that Kindraa Sainze retool their primary production facility on Shadow to resume limited manufacturing. Carrol directed Kindraa Sainze to trade newly produced 'Mechs to other Kindraa at reasonable rates, hoping the renewed presence of the totem 'Mech across all Fire Mandrill forces might kindle a new spirit of cooperation within the fractious Clan. Optimists among the Fire Mandrills saw this as a sign that the Clan could once again emerge as a powerful, united force.</p><p>The Mandrill's ultimate fate was tied to that of its parent Clan. During the Wars of Reaving in the 3070s, Clan Fire Mandrill was torn apart by a combination of external aggression and internal fragmentation. Attacks by Clan Steel Viper and Clan Star Adder devastated multiple Kindraa, and the death of Khan Carrol on Glory in 3073 shattered any remaining hope of organized resistance. Individual Kindraa were absorbed by other Clans or destroyed outright, and the Mandrill production line on Shadow almost certainly ceased operations as the Clan disintegrated. Any surviving examples likely remain scattered across the Clan Homeworlds in the hands of whatever forces absorbed their former operators.</p>

manufacturer:Kindraa Sainze Primary Production Facility

